<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<worksheet xml:id="rref-sage">
  <title>Reduced row echelon form</title>

  <p><alert>MTH 204:  January 20</alert></p>

  <introduction>
    <p>Remember that a matrix in reduced row echelon form is
    characterized by these properties:
    <ol>
      <li><p>If the entries in a row are all zero, then the same is
      true of any row below it.</p></li>
      <li><p>If we move across a row from left to right, the first
      nonzero entry we encounter is 1. We call this entry the
      <term>leading entry</term> in the row.</p></li>
      <li><p>The leading entry in any row is to the right of the leading
      entries in all the rows above it. </p></li>
      <li><p>A leading entry is the only nonzero entry in its
      column.</p></li>
    </ol>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
      Consider each of the following augmented matrices.  Determine if
      the matrix is in reduced row echelon form.  If it is not, perform a
      sequence of scaling, interchange, and replacement operations to
      obtain a row equivalent matrix that is in reduced row echelon form.
      Then use the reduced row echelon matrix to determine whether there
      is a single solution, infinitely many solutions, or no solutions.
      If there are infinitely many, identify free and basic variables.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{rrr|r}
          1 \amp -1 \amp 2 \amp -2 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{rrr|r}
          0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
          1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 8 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{rrr|r}
          1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{rrr|r}
          0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
          1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose that the reduced row echelon form of a matrix looks
        like
        <m>
        \left[
        \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
        1 \amp * \amp 0 \amp * \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp * \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
        \end{array}
        \right]
        </m>.
        What, if anything, does the last row tell you about the
        solution space?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that the reduced row echelon form of a matrix looks like
          <m>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
          1 \amp * \amp 0 \amp * \amp * \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp * \amp * \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
          </m>.
          What, if anything, does the last row tell you about the solution
          space?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a linear system has no solutions, how can you tell by looking at
          the reduced row echelon form of its augmented matrix.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>If a matrix is in reduced row echelon form, remember that
        the <term>leading entries</term> are the leftmost ones in a
        row.  We refer to the locations where the leading entries
        occur as <term>pivot positions.</term>
        </p>

        <p>
          Circle the pivot positions in the reduced row echelon form
          below:
          <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
            1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </md>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="0.9in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a system of linear equations has no solutions, what can
          you say about the pivot positions?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="0.9in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a system of linear equations has infinitely many solutions, what
          can you say about the pivot positions?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="0.9in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a system of linear equations has exactly one solution, what can
          you say about the pivot positions?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        There is a page of Sage cells at
        <url href="https://gvsu.edu/s/0Ng">gvsu.edu/s/0Ng</url>.  You
        will be using this frequently.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>To define a matrix, use 
            <cd>matrix([[1,2,3,4],[5,6,7,8]])</cd></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>You can give a matrix a name:
            <cd>A = matrix([[1,2,3,4],[5,6,7,8]])</cd></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>To find the reduced row echelon form,
            <cd>matrix([[1,2,3,4],[5,6,7,8]]).rref()</cd>
            or
            <cd>A.rref()</cd></p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        Use Sage to find the reduced row echelon form of the following
        augmented matrix.  Then describe the set of solutions to the
        associated system of linear equations:  is there 0, 1, or infinitely
        many solutions?  If there are infinitely many solutions, write the
        solutions in parametric form and identify free and basic
        variables.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{rrr|r}
            -1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
            2 \amp 4 \amp -1 \amp 5 \\
            1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 3
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use Sage to describe the solution space of the system of linear
          equations:
          <md>
            <mrow>
              -x_1 \amp  \amp  \amp  \amp  \amp  {}+{}  \amp 2x_4 \amp
              {}={}  \amp 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
             \amp  \amp 3x_2 \amp  {}+{}  \amp x_3 \amp  {}+{}  \amp 2x_4
             \amp  {}={}  \amp 3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4x_1 \amp  {}-{}  \amp 3x_2 \amp  \amp  \amp  {}+{}  \amp
              x_4 \amp  {}={}  \amp 14
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
             \amp  \amp 2x_2 \amp  {}+{}  \amp 2x_3 \amp  {}+{}  \amp x_4
             \amp  {}={}  \amp 1
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the reduced row echelon form of the augmented matrix
        <md>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          -2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
          -1 \amp 4 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
          3 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 2 \\
          1 \amp 5 \amp 3 \amp 7 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
        </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>coefficient matrix</term> is the portion of the
          augmented matrix to the left of the equal sign.  For
          instance, the coefficient matrix of the augmented matrix
          above is
          <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccc}
            -2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
            -1 \amp 4 \amp 1 \\
            3 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            1 \amp 5 \amp 3 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </md>.
          Find the reduced row echelon form of the coefficient matrix.  What you
          notice about the relationship between the reduced row echelon forms of
          the coefficient matrix and the augmented matrix?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write an example of an augmented matrix in reduced row echelon
          form whose associated system of linear equations has infinitely many
          solutions.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What feature of the pivot positions and the columns of the
          coefficient matrix causes there to be infinitely many
          solutions?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Write an example of an augmented matrix in reduced row echelon
      form whose associated system of linear equations has no solution
      (that is, is inconsistent).
      </p>
    </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What feature of the pivot positions of the coefficient matrix allows
          the system to be inconsistent?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <assemblage>
    <p>
      Make sure you can answer the following questions:
      <ol>
        <li><p>What is the reduced row echelon form of an augmented
        matrix and why is it useful?
        </p></li>
        <li><p>How does reduced row echelon form tell us that a system
        of equations has no solutions?</p></li>
        <li><p>How does reduced row echelon form tell us that a system of
        equations has a single solution?
        </p></li>
        <li><p>How can Sage help us find the reduced row echelon form
        of a matrix?
        </p></li>
        <li><p>What is a pivot position?</p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </assemblage>
</worksheet>

